2026-06-25 06:11:42,437 | INFO     | agent_framework  | trace=afb537c5685090303f6bf58606eec22a span=65f9636cd02b070e parent=- | {'role': 'tool', 'parts': [{'type': 'tool_call_response', 'id': '3gfe6p45r', 'response': '{\n  "results": [\n    {\n      "source": "FAB_Model_Risk_Management_Framework_v3.1",\n      "clause": "3.2",\n      "section": "3.2 Additional MEP Components - AI/ML Pricing Models",\n      "effective_date": "",\n      "stale": false,\n      "score": 0.0333,\n      "text": "## 3.2 Additional MEP Components - AI/ML Pricing Models\\n\\nFor AI/ML systems used in credit pricing (Tier 1), the MEP must additionally include:\\n\\n8. LLM and Agent Architecture: Description of the LLM backbone, agent orchestration framework, toolcalling design, and memory architecture. Version control information for all model components.\\n9. Pricing Floor Compliance Mechanism: Technical description of how the model enforces pricing floor constraints. Evidence that the system is incapable of recommending a rate below the applicable floor without generating a policy exception flag.\\n10. Data Grounding Evidence: Documentation of the RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation) architecture including: vector database configuration, document sources indexed, embedding model specifications, retrieval strategy, and re-indexing schedule.\\n11. Knowledge Graph Schema: For systems using a Knowledge Graph for rule lookup, documentation of the graph schema, node types, edge types, and data population procedures.\\n12. Explainability Artefact: A sample model output with the accompanying explanation, demonstrating that the explanation satisfies the requirements of CBUAE Circular 2024/BSE/047 Article 6.\\n13. Human-in-the-Loop Control Evidence: Technical description of the interrupt mechanism, approval workflow, and audit log structure. Confirmation that bypassing human approval is technically prevented.\\n14. Hallucination Risk Assessment: Assessment of the risk that the model may generate factually incorrect pricing information and the controls in place to detect and prevent such errors reaching end-users.\\n\\nIMPORTANT: The Data Grounding Evidence section (item 3 above) must demonstrate that all pricing floor values referenced by the model are sourced from the Knowledge Graph or RAG system, and not from the LLM\'s parametric knowledge. Parametric knowledge is not auditable and may not reflect current policy.\\n\\n## 4. Ongoing Monitoring Requirements\\n\\n## 4.1 Performance Monitoring\\n\\nAll production AI/ML pricing models must be monitored monthly against the following metrics:\\n\\n| Metric                         | Monitoring Frequency   | Alert Threshold                                   |\\n|--------------------------------|------------------------|---------------------------------------------------|\\n| Pricing floor breach rate      | Daily                  | Any breach triggers immediate investigation       |\\n| Human override rate            | Monthly                | > 20% override rate triggers model review         |\\n| Recommendation acceptance rate | Monthly                | < 60% acceptance rate triggers performance review |\\n\\n| RAG retrieval freshness score   | Weekly   | Average freshness < 0.80 triggers re- indexing             |\\n|---------------------------------|----------|------------------------------------------------------------|\\n| Knowledge Graph staleness       | Weekly   | Any node with effective_date > 6 months old without review |\\n| LLM response latency            | Daily    | p95 > 5 seconds triggers infrastructure review             |\\n| Explanation completeness score  | Monthly  | < 90% complete explanations triggers model review          |\\n\\n## 5. Incident Reporting\\n\\nA model incident is defined as any event in which an AI/ML model produces an output that: (a) breaches a pricing floor; (b) results in customer detriment; (c) triggers a regulatory notification; or (d) results in a financial loss attributable to model error.\\n\\nAll model incidents must be reported to the Model Risk Management team within 24 hours of detection, and to the CBUAE within 30 calendar days where the incident is material (threshold: financial impact &gt; AED 1 million or regulatory breach)."\n    },\n    {\n      "source": "CBUAE_Circular_2024_BSE_047_AI_Governance",\n      "clause": "6.2",\n      "section": "6.2 Customer Transparency",\n      "effective_date": "",\n      "stale": false,\n      "score": 0.0325,\n      "text": "## 6.2 Customer Transparency\\n\\n6.2.1 Where the terms offered to a customer (including pricing) have been materially influenced by an AI/ML system, and a customer requests an explanation of how their terms were determined, the LFI must be able to provide a meaningful explanation of the factors that influenced the outcome. The LFI is not required to disclose proprietary model architecture or training data.\\n\\n## Article 7 - Data Governance for AI Systems\\n\\n## 7.1 Data Quality\\n\\n7.1.1 LFIs must implement data quality controls to ensure that data used to train, validate, and operate AI/ML systems is accurate, complete, timely, and fit for purpose. Data quality assessments must be documented and reviewed at least annually. 7.1.2 For AI systems used in credit pricing, the following data governance requirements apply in addition to the\\n\\ngeneral requirements in Article 7.1.1:\\n\\n- Interest rate and FTP data used as inputs must be sourced directly from authorised internal Treasury systems and must not be manually overridden without a documented audit trail.\\n- Client risk rating data used as inputs must be sourced from the LFI\'s credit systems and must reflect the most recently approved internal credit rating.\\n- Market benchmark data (e.g., peer pricing) used as inputs must be sourced from identified, approved data providers and must be date-stamped.\\n\\n## 7.2 Data Retention and Lineage\\n\\n7.2.1 Complete data lineage - from source system to model input to model output - must be documented and retained for all HIGH-risk AI/ML system predictions. This lineage must support reconstruction of any recommendation for audit or regulatory review purposes.\\n\\n## Article 8 - Regulatory Reporting and Supervisory Access\\n\\n8.1 LFIs must submit an annual AI/ML Systems Return to the Central Bank of the UAE by 31 March each year, covering the preceding calendar year. The format of the Return will be prescribed by the Central Bank. 8.2 In addition to the annual Return, LFIs must notify the Central Bank within 30 calendar days of: (a) initial deployment of any new HIGH-risk AI/ML system; (b) any material modification to an existing HIGH-risk system; (c) any AI-related incident that results in material consumer detriment or regulatory breach. 8.3 The Central Bank reserves the right to conduct on-site or off-site examinations of LFIs\' AI/ML systems, governance frameworks, model documentation, and validation records at any time. LFIs must provide full\\n\\ncooperation with such examinations.\\n\\nNON-COMPLIANCE: LFIs that fail to comply with the requirements of this Circular by the applicable deadline will be subject to supervisory action, which may include direction to suspend the use of non-compliant AI/ML systems, imposition of administrative penalties, or other measures as provided under Federal Decree-Law No. 14 of 2018.\\n\\n## Article 9 - Transitional Provisions\\n\\n9.1 LFIs that are currently operating AI/ML systems in material business processes as of the issue date of this Circular must complete a gap assessment against the requirements herein within 60 days of the effective date (1 July 2024) and submit a remediation plan to the Central Bank. 9.2 Existing HIGH-risk systems that have not undergone independent model validation must complete validation\\n\\nby 31 December 2024 for Tier 1 institutions, or by 30 June 2025 for all other LFIs.\\n\\nIssued under the authority of the Central Bank of the UAE Banking Supervision &amp; Examination Department  |  Abu Dhabi, March 2024"\n    },\n    {\n      "source": "CBUAE_Circular_2024_BSE_047_AI_Governance",\n      "clause": "2.2.1",\n      "section": "CENTRAL BANK OF THE UNITED ARAB EMIRATES",\n      "effective_date": "",\n      "stale": false,\n      "score": 0.0318,\n      "text": "## CENTRAL BANK OF THE UNITED ARAB EMIRATES\\n\\nBanking Supervision &amp; Examination Department\\n\\n## SUPERVISORY CIRCULAR\\n\\n## No. 2024/BSE/047\\n\\n## Governance and Risk Management Requirements for Artificial Intelligence and Machine Learning Systems in Licensed Financial Institutions\\n\\n| Circular Reference   | CBUAE/BSE/2024/047                                                                                 |\\n|----------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\\n| Issue Date           | 15 March 2024                                                                                      |\\n| Effective Date       | 1 July 2024                                                                                        |\\n| Addressed To         | Chief Executive Officers and Chief Risk Officers of all Licensed Financial Institutions in the UAE |\\n| Subject              | AI/ML Governance, Model Risk Management, and Consumer Protection Requirements                      |\\n| Supersedes           | CBUAE/BSE/2022/031 (Guidance on Automated Decision-Making)                                         |\\n| Compliance Deadline  | 31 December 2024 for Tier 1 institutions; 30 June 2025 for all others                              |\\n\\n## Article 1 - Purpose, Scope and Legal Basis\\n\\n1.1 This Circular is issued pursuant to the powers vested in the Central Bank of the UAE under Federal DecreeLaw No. 14 of 2018 regarding the Central Bank and Organisation of Financial Institutions and Activities, as amended, and the accompanying Executive Regulations. 1.2 This Circular establishes minimum standards for the governance, development, deployment, monitoring, and decommissioning of Artificial Intelligence (AI) and Machine Learning (ML) systems used by Licensed Financial Institutions (LFIs) in the UAE in connection with credit decisions, risk management, pricing of financial products, customer service, fraud detection, and any other material business function. 1.3 This Circular applies to all LFIs licensed and supervised by the Central Bank of the UAE, including but not limited to national banks, foreign bank branches, finance companies, exchange houses, and payment service providers, to the extent that they deploy AI or ML systems in material business processes. 1.4 For the purposes of this Circular, an AI/ML system is considered to be deployed in a \'material business process\' where its outputs directly or indirectly influence decisions that: (a) affect a customer\'s access to or terms of a financial product or service; (b) generate recommendations that are presented to employees or customers as a basis for financial action; or (c) are used to calculate, estimate, or propose prices, rates, fees, or other commercial terms for financial products.\\n\\nIMPORTANT: The pricing of credit facilities, including the use of AI-generated pricing recommendations for corporate loans, revolving facilities, or any structured credit product, is explicitly classified as a material business process under Article 1.4(c). All requirements in this Circular apply to such systems.\\n\\n## Article 2 - Governance Framework Requirements\\n\\n## 2.1 Board and Senior Management Accountability\\n\\n2.1.1 The Board of Directors of every LFI deploying AI/ML systems in material business processes must adopt and maintain a written AI Governance Policy. This policy must be reviewed and re-approved by the Board at least annually. 2.1.2 A designated member of senior management, at a level no lower than Chief Risk Officer or equivalent, must be appointed as the AI Risk Officer responsible for overseeing the implementation of this Circular. 2.1.3 The AI Governance Policy must address, at minimum: (a) the LFI\'s risk appetite for AI-related risks; (b) accountability structures for AI development and deployment; (c) human oversight requirements; (d) model\\n\\ninventory management; (e) consumer protection obligations; and (f) regulatory reporting obligations.\\n\\n## 2.2 AI Model Inventory\\n\\n2.2.1 Every LFI must maintain a centralised, up-to-date AI Model Inventory covering all AI/ML systems deployed in material business processes. The inventory must be made available to the Central Bank upon request.\\n\\n2.2.2 For each model in the inventory, the following minimum information must be recorded:\\n\\n- Model name, version, and unique identifier.\\n- Business function and processes in which the model is deployed.\\n- Date of initial deployment and date of most recent material update.\\n- Model owner (business function) and model developer (technology/data team).\\n- Validation status and date of last independent validation.\\n- Current monitoring status (active / under review / decommissioned).\\n- Risk classification (High / Medium / Low) as determined under Article 4.\\n\\n## Article 3 - Model Risk Management\\n\\n## 3.1 Model Development Standards\\n\\n3.1.1 All AI/ML models deployed in material business processes must be developed in accordance with sound model development practices, including but not limited to: clearly documented model objectives; appropriate training data governance; out-of-time and out-of-sample testing; and documentation of model limitations and known failure modes.\\n\\n3.1.2 Training data used for models that influence credit pricing or credit decisions must be sourced from reliable, auditable data systems. Data lineage must be documented from source to model input."\n    },\n    {\n      "source": "FAB_Model_Risk_Management_Framework_v3.1",\n      "clause": "Section 2",\n      "section": "FIRST ABU DHABI BANK",\n      "effective_date": "",\n      "stale": false,\n      "score": 0.0318,\n      "text": "## FIRST ABU DHABI BANK\\n\\nGroup Risk Management\\n\\n## MODEL RISK MANAGEMENT FRAMEWORK\\n\\nAI / ML and Quantitative Model Governance Standards\\n\\n| Document Reference   | FAB-MRM-FW-2024-v3.1                   |\\n|----------------------|----------------------------------------|\\n| Version              | 3.1                                    |\\n| Effective Date       | 1 January 2024                         |\\n| Owner                | Chief Risk Officer                     |\\n| Author               | Model Risk Management team, Group Risk |\\n| Approved By          | Board Risk & Compliance Committee      |\\n| Classification       | Confidential -Internal Use Only        |\\n\\n## 1. Framework Purpose and Scope\\n\\nThis Model Risk Management (MRM) Framework establishes FAB\'s enterprise-wide standards for the identification, measurement, management, and governance of model risk. It applies to all quantitative models, AI/ML systems, and automated decision-making tools used within FAB Group that are classified as material under Section 2 of this Framework.\\n\\nThe Framework is aligned with internationally recognised standards, including the US Federal Reserve SR 11-7 guidance on model risk management and the CBUAE Circular No. 2024/BSE/047 on AI/ML governance.\\n\\nSCOPE: This Framework explicitly covers AI-based pricing recommendation systems, including large language model (LLM)-based agents used to propose credit facility pricing, as these systems generate quantitative outputs used in material business decisions.\\n\\n## 2. Model Risk Classification\\n\\nFAB classifies all models into three tiers based on materiality and the potential consequences of model error:\\n\\n| Tier            | Criteria                                                                                                   | Examples                                                             | Validation Requirement                                |\\n|-----------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------|\\n| Tier 1 (High)   | Direct P&L impact or credit decision influence above AED 10M; regulatory capital models; pricing AI agents | IFRS 9 impairment models · Credit pricing AI · Stress testing models | Full independent validation before deployment; annual |\\n| Tier 2 (Medium) | Indirect P&L impact; operational models with significant throughput                                        | Customer segmentation · behavioural scoring models                   | Targeted validation; biennial                         |\\n| Tier 3 (Low)    | Minimal impact; administrative or back-office tools                                                        | Document classification · internal scheduling tools                  | Self-certification by owner                           |\\n\\n## 3. Model Evidence Pack Requirements\\n\\nFor every Tier 1 and Tier 2 model deployed in production, a complete Model Evidence Pack (MEP) must be maintained and updated following any material model change. The MEP is the primary audit document for model risk purposes and must be made available to internal audit, CBUAE examiners, and external auditors upon request.\\n\\n## 3.1 Mandatory MEP Components - All Models\\n\\n1. Model Overview: Name, version, unique model ID, purpose, business function, date of initial development, and current deployment status.\\n2. Model Design Documentation: Theoretical basis, mathematical formulation, assumptions and limitations, data sources, and feature engineering approach.\\n3. Development and Training Data: Data dictionary, data sources, data quality assessment, training period, and any data preprocessing or transformations applied.\\n\\n4. Performance Metrics: In-sample and out-of-sample performance; benchmark comparison against challenger models or expert judgment; results of cross-validation.\\n5. Validation Record: Independent validation findings, identified weaknesses, management responses, and outstanding remediation actions.\\n6. Model Limitations and Known Failure Modes: Documented scenarios in which the model may perform poorly or produce unreliable outputs, and the controls in place to mitigate such failures.\\n7. Human Override Record: Summary statistics of human override rates for the preceding 12-month period, including trend analysis."\n    }\n  ],\n  "total_results": 4,\n  "freshness_warning": false,\n  "latency_ms": 293.38\n}'}]}
2026-06-25 06:11:44,401 | INFO     | agent_framework  | trace=afb537c5685090303f6bf58606eec22a span=65f9636cd02b070e parent=- | {'role': 'assistant', 'parts': [{'type': 'text', 'content': 'Based on the FAB Model Risk Management Framework and CBUAE Circular 2024/BSE/047, here is the definition and reporting timeline for model incidents:\n\n### What Constitutes a Model Incident\nAccording to the **FAB Model Risk Management Framework (Section 5)**, a model incident is any event where an AI/ML model produces an output that:\n1. Breaches a pricing floor;\n2. Results in customer detriment;\n3. Triggers a regulatory notification; or\n4. Results in a financial loss attributable to model error.\n\n### Reporting Deadlines\nThere are two distinct reporting deadlines depending on the audience and materiality of the incident:\n\n*   **Internal Reporting (FAB Model Risk Management Team):** \n    All model incidents must be reported within **24 hours** of detection.\n    *Source: FAB Model Risk Management Framework v3.1, Section 5.*\n\n*   **Regulatory Reporting (CBUAE):** \n    If the incident is deemed "material," it must be reported to the Central Bank of the UAE within **30 calendar days** of occurrence. \n    *Source: CBUAE Circular 2024/BSE/047, Article 8.2 & FAB Model Risk Management Framework v3.1, Section 5.*\n\n**Note on Materiality:** Under FAB policy, an incident is typically considered reportable to the CBUAE if the financial impact exceeds **AED 1 million** or if it constitutes a regulatory breach.'}]}
