e · 3.1.1]\n*   **Credit Data Governance:** Models influencing credit or pricing must use data sourced from reliable, auditable systems with fully documented data lineage from source to input. [CBUAE_Circular_2024_BSE_047_AI_Governance · 3.1.2]\n\n### 4. Data Quality and Lineage\n*   Institutions must implement data quality controls (ensuring accuracy, completeness, and timeliness), with assessments documented and reviewed at least annually. [CBUAE_Circular_2024_BSE_047_AI_Governance · 7.1.1]\n*   For **HIGH-risk** AI systems, complete data lineage from the source system through to the model output must be retained to support audit and regulatory review. [CBUAE_Circular_2024_BSE_047_AI_Governance · 7.2.1]\n\n### 5. Consumer Protection and Transparency\n*   If a customer requests an explanation for terms (such as pricing) materially influenced by an AI system, the LFI must provide a meaningful explanation'}]}
2026-06-25 11:26:44,364 | INFO     | agent_framework  | trace=366cb0289a4ac3910871ce44aa2e065e span=553c277b23335918 parent=- | {'role': 'assistant', 'parts': [{'type': 'text', 'content': '**AI Governance Requirements – CBUAE Supervisory Circular\u202fNo.\u202f2024/BSE/047 (issued\u202f15\u202fMarch\u202f2024)**  \n\n---\n\n### 1. Governance and Accountability  \n- **AI Governance Policy** – “The Board of Directors must adopt and maintain a written AI Governance Policy, which must be reviewed and re‑approved at least annually.”\u202f[Source: CBUAE_Circular_2024_BSE_047_AI_Governance\u202f·\u202f2.1.1]  \n- **Senior Management Oversight** – “A designated senior executive (at the level of Chief Risk Officer or above) must be appointed as the ‘AI Risk Officer’ to oversee implementation.”\u202f[Source: CBUAE_Circular_2024_BSE_047_AI_Governance\u202f·\u202f2.1.2]  \n- **Policy Content** – “The policy must explicitly address the institution’s risk appetite, accountability structures, human‑oversight requirements, and consumer‑protection obligations.”\u202f[Source: CBUAE_Circular_2024_BSE_047_AI_Governance\u202f·\u202f2.1.3]  \n\n### 2. Centralised AI Model Inventory  \n- “Every LFI must maintain a centralised, up‑to‑date inventory of all AI/ML systems used in material business processes.”\u202f[Source: CBUAE_Circular_2024_BSE_047_AI_Governance\u202f·\u202f2.2.1]  \n- “The inventory must record the model’s unique identifier, business function, deployment dates, owner/developer, last validation date, and its assigned risk classification (High, Medium, or Low).”\u202f[Source: CBUAE_Circular_2024_BSE_047_AI_Governance\u202f·\u202f2.2.2]  \n\n### 3. Model Risk Management & Development  \n- **Development Standards** – “All models must be developed using sound practices, including documented objectives, out‑of‑time/sample testing, and a clear record of model limitations and known failure modes.”\u202f[Source: CBUAE_Circular_2024_BSE_047_AI_Governance\u202f·\u202f3.1.1]  \n- **Credit Data Governance** – “Models influencing credit or pricing must use data sourced from reliable, auditable systems with fully documented data lineage from source to input.”\u202f[Source: CBUAE_Circular_2024_BSE_047_AI_Governance\u202f·\u202f3.1.2]  \n\n### 4. Data Quality and Lineage  \n- “Institutions must implement data quality controls (ensuring accuracy, completeness, and timeliness), with assessments documented and reviewed at least annually.”\u202f[Source: CBUAE_Circular_2024_BSE_047_AI_Governance\u202f·\u202f7.1.1]  \n- For **high‑risk** AI systems: “Complete data lineage from the source system through to the model output must be retained to support audit and regulatory review.”\u202f[Source: CBUAE_Circular_2024_BSE_047_AI_Governance\u202f·\u202f7.2.1]  \n\n### 5. Consumer Protection and Transparency  \n- “If a customer requests an explanation for terms (such as pricing) materially influenced by an AI system, the LFI must provide a meaningful explanation.”\u202f[Source: CBUAE_Circular_2024_BSE_047_AI_Governance\u202f·\u202f(Clause not shown in excerpt)]  \n\n---\n\n**Summary:** The circular mandates a formal AI Governance Policy approved by the Board, a senior‑level AI Risk Officer, a detailed inventory of AI/ML models, rigorous development and data‑quality standards (with heightened controls for high‑risk models), and transparent, consumer‑focused explanations when AI influences decisions. All elements must be documented, regularly reviewed, and aligned with the institution’s risk appetite and regulatory expectations.'}]}
